				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">As an approximation, a single character of a password can hold 5 bits of information, or one out of 32 values. This means five 2-state variables (key owned or not), three 3-state variables (key not picked up, key in inventory, key transported to corresponding lock), two 5-state variables (this might be your &quot;special status&quot;), or one of each. But if you end up with more than about 70 bits or 14 characters of data that you need to track, it becomes unwieldy to enter the password at the start of the session. If you run a block cipher over the password followed by a consistency check on what doors can be unlocked before others, you might be able to get away with one or two fewer check digits because the consistency check will pick up more invalid passwords, but that's it.<br /><br />For more specific information, we will need how many is &quot;biggish&quot;.</div>

